04911nam a22006735i 9780822379447DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19961996ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223794477 a10.1515/97808223794472doi  a(DE-B1597)554696  a(OCoLC)1154551727  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN98.P75bG39 1996 7aPSY0000002bisacsh04a801/.9500aGaze and Voice as Love Objects :bSIC 1 /cSlavoj Zizek, Renata Salecl. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1996] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b9 b&w photographs, 4 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSIC ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPART I GAZE,VOICE -- tThe Object Voice -- tPhilosophers' Blind Man's Buff -- tKilling Gazes, Killing in the Gaze: On Michael Powell's Peeping Tom -- t"I Hear You with My Eyes"; or, The Invisible Master -- tPART II LOVE OBJECTS -- tAt First Sight -- tOn the Sexual Production of Western Subjectivity; or, Saint Augustine as a Social Democrat -- tI Can't Love You Unless I Give You Up -- t"There Is No Sexual Relationship" -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe gaze entices, inspects, fascinates. The voice hypnotizes, seduces, disarms. Are gaze and voice part of the relationship we call love . . . or hate? If so, what part? How do they function? This provocative book examines love as the mediating entity in the essential antagonism between the sexes, and gaze and voice as love's medium. The contributors proceed from the Lacanian premise that "there is no sexual relationship," that the sexes are in no way complementary and that love-figured in the gaze and the voice -embodies the promise and impossibility of any relation between them.The first detailed Lacanian elaboration of this topic, Gaze and Voice as Love Objects examines the status of gaze, voice, and love in philosophy from Plato to Kant, in ideology from early Christianity to contemporary cynicism, in music from Hildegard of Bingen to Richard Wagner, in literature from Edith Wharton's Age of Innocence to Kazuo Ishiguro's The Remains of the Day, and in cinema from Michael Powell's Peeping Tom to Kieslowski's A Short Film on Love. Throughout, the contributors seek to show that the conflict between the sexes is the site of a larger battle over the destiny of modernity. With insights into the underlying target of racist and sexist violence, this book offers surprising revelations into the nature of an ancient enigma-love.Contributors. Elisabeth Bronfen, Mladen Dolar, Fredric Jameson, Renata Salecl, Slavoj Žižek, Alenka Zupancic  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aCriticism. 0aGaze in literature. 0aPsychoanalysis and literature. 0aVoice in literature. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh1 aZupančič, Alenka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBronfen, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJameson, Fredric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDolar, Mladen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalecl, Renata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalecl, Renata, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aZizek, Slavoj, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aŽižek, Slavoj, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZizek, Slavoj, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822379447zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://w